## 9. Risk Factors

- **Industry-specific risks:** NYC trade-waste is heavily regulated by the Business Integrity Commission, including rate caps. The Commercial Waste Zone rollout is reshaping the broader carting market — though C&D roll-off is exempt, any putrescible-carting revenue the company has would be exposed. Construction-driven demand is cyclical.
- **Financial risks:** Probable customer concentration among a few large GCs and city agencies (undisclosed). Only one year of financials disclosed — cannot confirm the growth trend or margin stability. "Cash flow" basis (SDE vs. adjusted EBITDA) must be confirmed; if it includes owner add-backs, true EBITDA may be lower and the effective multiple higher than 4.73x.
- **Operational risks:** Asset-heavy fleet implies ongoing capex for truck replacement and container maintenance. Key driver/dispatcher retention and CDL labor availability in NYC are operational pressure points. Management is stated to stay — confirm depth and contracts.
- **Regulatory / legal:** Confirm active BIC carter registration/authorization in good standing; review any BIC violations, environmental (NYSDEC C&D facility) compliance, and DOT/FMCSA fleet safety record. NYC Comptroller reporting has flagged carters with safety/environmental violations — run a clean-record check.
- **Deal-specific conditions:**
  - **Negotiate from 4.73x to ≤4.0x EBITDA (~$6.72M) as a condition of the deal.**
  - Obtain 2022–2024 P&Ls and balance sheets to verify the 3-year revenue/profit growth trend.
  - Obtain top-5/top-10 customer concentration breakdown.
  - Confirm FTE headcount and the SDE-vs-EBITDA basis of the $1.68M figure.
  - Confirm BIC registration and the C&D-exempt vs. CWZ-covered revenue split.

